<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[816,1474,1925,2045]" lastBlockId="5.[113,772,1138,1386]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
DISTRIBUTION. Only known from the type locality: Culebrita Island (
<geoCoordinate box="[897,1021,1989,2013]" degrees="18" direction="north" minutes="05" orientation="latitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" precision="15" seconds="34" value="18.09278">18°05'34&quot;N</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[1031,1164,1989,2013]" degrees="66" direction="west" minutes="54" orientation="longitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" precision="15" seconds="32" value="-66.90889">66°54'32&quot;W</geoCoordinate>
). This species was described on the basis of a single adult female, which is the only known specimen. On the apical area of the left comb of the 
<typeStatus box="[680,772,1138,1162]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[121,202,1170,1194]" captionStart="Figures 12−14" captionStartId="6.[116,193,1336,1358]" captionTargetBox="[113,1474,234,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-362@6.[113,1474,234,1325]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 12−14: Microtityus spp., pectines. Figure 12. M. vieques, male holotype, basal middle lamella conspicuously enlarged, modified from Teruel et al. (2015: fig. 2b). Figure 13. M. santosi, female holotype, basal plate and the distal area of the left comb, showing two egg-like organisms firmly attached (outside square), modified from Teruel et al. (2014: fig. 5c). Figure 14. M. borincanus, female holotype, basal plate, modified from Teruel et al. (2014: fig. 2c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648520/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) there are two egg-like organisms solidly attached, similar to those found on some scorpions and a Colombian schizomid (
<bibRefCitation author="ARMAS" box="[235,372,1234,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" pagination="239 - 240" refId="ref3707" refString="ARMAS, L. F. DE. 2003. On two enigmatic organisms associated with some Mexican and Antillean scorpions. Revista Iberica de Aracnologia, 7: 239 - 240." type="journal article" year="2003">Armas, 2003</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 2; Delgado-Santa &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="DE ARMAS" box="[630,768,1234,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" pagination="37 - 45" refId="ref3980" refString="DELGADO-SANTA, L. &amp; L. F. DE ARMAS. 2013. Tres nuevos Hubbardiinae (Schizomida: Hubbardiidae) de Colombia. Revista Iberica de Aracnologia, 22: 37 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Armas, 2013</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3B), which were overlooked by Teruel et al. (2014). This enigmatic organism resembles an insect or mite egg, but its real origin is yet unknown. It also has been observed on an 
<taxonomicName box="[703,771,1330,1354]" class="Arachnida" family="Diplocentridae" genus="Oiclus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[703,771,1330,1354]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Oiclus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1880" box="[156,314,1362,1386]" class="Arachnida" family="Diplocentridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Diplocentridae</taxonomicName>
) from 
<collectingCountry box="[385,472,1362,1386]" name="Saint Kitts and Nevis" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">St. Kitts</collectingCountry>
, Lesser Antilles (pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
